<DOC><DOCNO> AP880311-0284 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-11-88 0931EST</FILEID><FIRST>u f PM-Colt 1stLd-Writethru   03-11 0345</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Colt, 1st Ld-Writethru,0358</SECOND><HEAD>Colt Industries To Be Taken Private In Leveraged Buyout</HEAD><NOTE>Eds: SUBS first 2 grafs to CORRECT total figure, which includesoptions and expenses, and total outstanding shares.</NOTE><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Colt Industries Inc., a major defense contractorand industrial concern, has agreed to be taken private in a $660million leveraged buyout led by senior management and theinvestment firm Morgan Stanley Group Inc.   The board of Colt, whose name may be best known from itsfirearms business, approved an offer of $17 a share for all of itsapproximately 31.65 million common shares outstanding lateWednesday and announced the plan on Thursday. The price of Coltstock options and expenses was included in the total price of thebuyout.   The offer was subject to several conditions, including amajority of the shares being tendered.   Colt shares surged $4.87{ to $18.12{ on the New York StockExchange on Thursday, indicating some speculators believed an offerhigher than the group's $17 a share bid would emerge.   Under the transaction, Colt would become a wholly-ownedsubsidiary of Colt Holdings Inc., a new company formed by themanagement team and Morgan Stanley Leveraged Equity Fund II, Coltstated. About $1.4 billion of Colt debt would remain outstanding,it said.   The Morgan Stanley Leveraged Equity Fund II is a limitedpartnership that invests in leveraged buyouts, or deals in which acompany is acquired largely with borrowed funds repaid through thetarget company's profits or sale of its assets.   Colt said Morgan Stanley and its equity fund unit have agreed toprovide $460 million in short-term bridge financing for ColtHoldings, which would be repaid through a public or privateoffering of long-term debt.   Investors in Colt Holdings would put up another $200 million,Colt said.   Colt Chairman David I. Margolis said the merger agreement wouldgive Colt ``the opportunity to establish and implement a moreaggressive business program, including acquisition, than we couldhave undertaken alone.''   Colt is a leading supplier of aerospace, automotive andindustrial products. It employs about 22,000 people.</TEXT></DOC>